# Use Impeccable for all UI work

This project uses the [Impeccable](https://impeccable.style) design skill —
installed locally at `.cursor/skills/impeccable/`. It exists to keep the AI
from defaulting to AI-slop UI patterns.

## Trigger

Engage Impeccable any time you are about to:

- create or modify HTML, CSS, JSX, TSX, Vue, Svelte, or any markup that
  renders UI
- restyle or reskin an existing surface
- tweak typography, spacing, color, motion, or copy
- add a new screen, component, modal, dialog, empty state, error state, or
  setting
- "just make this look nicer" / "polish this" / "make this more modern"

If the request is purely backend or non-UI, ignore this rule.

## Required preflight (do not skip)

Before any UI edit, follow Impeccable's setup gates from
`.cursor/skills/impeccable/SKILL.md`:

1. **Load context.** Read `PRODUCT.md` and `DESIGN.md` at the project root.
   They are the source of truth for register, users, tone, anti-references,
   color tokens, typography, motion, and components.
2. **Identify register.** This project's `PRODUCT.md` declares register
   `product`. Apply `.cursor/skills/impeccable/reference/product.md`. Do not
   apply `brand.md` rules unless explicitly redesigning a marketing surface.
3. **Pick the right command.** When the user's request matches a command
   (`polish`, `audit`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `clarify`, `adapt`, `animate`,
   `colorize`, `delight`, `distill`, `harden`, `layout`, `optimize`,
   `typeset`, `extract`, `critique`), follow that command's reference file
   in `.cursor/skills/impeccable/reference/`.

State Impeccable is in use in your response so the user can audit the
choices.

## Hard constraints (absolute bans)

Refuse — and silently rewrite — any of these patterns when generating UI:

- `background-clip: text` with a gradient (gradient text). Use weight + size
  for emphasis instead.
- The "hero-metric template" (huge number + tiny label + supporting stats +
  decorative gradient). The results screen, dashboard headers, and stats
  surfaces must avoid it.
- Decorative `backdrop-filter: blur(...)` (glassmorphism as default).
  Allowed only when it serves a real visual hierarchy purpose.
- Side-stripe borders (`border-left`/`border-right` >1px as a colored
  accent on cards / list items / alerts).
- `#000` / `#fff` literals, or pure-saturation hex on neutrals. Use OKLCH;
  tint every neutral toward the brand hue (`oklch(... 0.02-0.03 270)`).
- `color: white` on text. Use `var(--text)` (a tinted near-white) or a
  per-state OKLCH value for high-contrast chips.
- Modals as the first instinct. Exhaust inline / progressive alternatives
  before reaching for a dialog. Modals are reserved for destructive
  confirmations.
- Em dashes (`—`) and double hyphens (`--`) in copy. Use commas, colons,
  semicolons, periods, or parentheses.
- Identical-card grids of icon + heading + text repeated endlessly.

## Color and typography

- Use the OKLCH tokens defined in `:root` of `static/styles.css`. Do not
  introduce new ad-hoc colors; if a new shade is needed, add it as a token
  with an OKLCH value and document it in `DESIGN.md`.
- One typeface family: `Inter, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe
  UI", system-ui, sans-serif`. No display fonts in product UI.
- Fixed `rem` / `px` scale. No `clamp()`-driven fluid headlines.
- Type ratio ≈ 1.2 between sizes; weight + size carry hierarchy.

## Motion

- 150ms for color/border transitions, 250ms for reveal/feedback, no longer.
- Easing: `ease-out` only (`var(--ease)`, an ease-out-quart curve). No
  bounce, no elastic.
- Animate transforms and opacity. Never animate layout properties (`width`,
  `height`, `padding`, `margin`, etc.) for state transitions. The results
  bar's `width` animation is the documented exception because it represents
  a value, not a state change.

## Components

- Every interactive element ships with: default, hover, focus-visible,
  active, disabled. Don't ship without focus-visible.
- Buttons ≥ 44px tall, `touch-action: manipulation`,
  `-webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent`.
- Mobile (≤ 640px): primary action stacks full-width; modals get full-width
  buttons; tap targets stay ≥ 44px.

## Output discipline

When you make UI changes, your final response must include:

1. A one-line statement that Impeccable was applied and which register
   you used (`product` for this project).
2. A short list of the impeccable principles you applied or violations you
   removed (e.g. "Replaced gradient text with weight contrast on the
   results headline").
3. A note if you intentionally bent a rule, with the reason.

If `PRODUCT.md` or `DESIGN.md` is missing, ambiguous, or contradicted by
the user's request, ask before guessing — never synthesize design intent
from the prompt alone.
